BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
This inequality has terms with denominators [`[$den[0]]\text{,}`] [`[$den[1]]\text{,}`] and [`[$den[2]]\text{.}`] The least common multiple of these is [`[$lcd]\text{.}`] So the first step in solving this inequality can be to multiply on each side by [`[$lcd]\text{.}`]

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
[$lcd]\left([$left]\right) \amp[$texcmp] [$lcd]\left([$right]\right)\\
[$leftsol[0]] \amp[$texcmp] [$rightsol[0]]\\
[$leftsol[1]] \amp[$texcmp] [$rightsol[1]]\\
[$leftsol[2]] \amp[$texcmp] [$rightsol[2]]\\
[$leftsol[3]] \amp[$texcmp] [$rightsol[3]]
\end{aligned}
```]

The solution set is [`\{x\mid x [$texcmp] [$sol]\}`] using set-builder notation. In interval notation, we have [`[$in]\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

